---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Hero from '../../components/Hero.astro';
import ServiceCard from '../../components/ServiceCard.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import Icon from '../../components/Icon.astro';
import { APP_SERVICES } from '../../lib/site';

const title = 'Mobile app development for iOS and Android';
const description =
  'Apriori Studio designs, builds and ships native iPhone and Android apps. Marketplaces, on-demand services, booking and fitness — end-to-end, from idea to App Store and Google Play.';

const ICONS: Record<string, 'grid' | 'truck' | 'calendar' | 'heart'> = {
  '/apps/marketplace': 'grid',
  '/apps/on-demand': 'truck',
  '/apps/booking': 'calendar',
  '/apps/fitness': 'heart',
};
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <Hero image="/heroes/apps.webp" tint="navy">
    <span class="kicker text-amber-300">Mobile apps</span>
    <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-5xl font-semibold tracking-tight leading-[1.05] hero-shadow">
      Native mobile apps,<br class="hidden md:block" /> designed and shipped
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-5 text-lg text-slate-200/95 max-w-2xl hero-shadow">
      iPhone and Android apps — fully native where it matters, cross-platform where it makes
      sense. We handle the parts most studios won't: store submission, push, privacy
      declarations, and ongoing updates after launch.
    </p>
  </Hero>

  <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-5 py-12 md:py-16">
    <Breadcrumbs items={[
      { href: '/', label: 'Home' },
      { href: '/apps', label: 'Mobile apps' },
    ]} />

    <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-5 mb-14 reveal">
      {APP_SERVICES.map((s) => (
        <a href={s.href} class="group block p-6 bg-white border border-[var(--color-border)] rounded-xl hover:border-[var(--color-accent)] hover:shadow-md transition-all">
          <div class="w-11 h-11 rounded-lg bg-[var(--color-ink)] text-white flex items-center justify-center mb-4 group-hover:bg-[var(--color-accent)] transition-colors">
            <Icon name={ICONS[s.href]} size={22} />
          </div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-[var(--color-ink)] group-hover:text-[var(--color-accent)] transition-colors mb-2">{s.title}</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-ink-soft)] leading-relaxed mb-4">{s.blurb}</p>
          <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-sm font-medium text-[var(--color-accent)]">
            Learn more <Icon name="arrow-right" size={14} class="group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform" />
          </span>
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>

    <div class="prose-body max-w-3xl">
      <h2>How we build mobile apps</h2>
      <p>
        Mobile is harder than web in ways most clients don't realise until they've shipped one.
        Two stores with two review processes, each with their own rules. A device fleet
        spanning ten years of hardware. App lifecycles where users keep the app installed but
        don't open it for months. Privacy frameworks that shift every iOS release. We handle
        all of this so you can focus on the product.
      </p>

      <h3>Native, cross-platform, or hybrid?</h3>
      <p>
        For apps that need full access to platform features (background location, complex
        gestures, AR, advanced camera) and where performance matters, we build native — Swift
        for iOS, Kotlin for Android. For most business apps where the UI is fairly standard
        and the value is in the features, we use <strong>React Native</strong> or
        <strong>Flutter</strong>: one codebase, both platforms, faster to build, easier to
        keep in sync. We'll explain the trade-off honestly for your specific app — neither
        approach is "better," they're just suited to different jobs.
      </p>

      <h3>Design that respects each platform</h3>
      <p>
        iOS users expect iOS conventions; Android users expect Material Design; copying one
        platform's patterns onto the other makes both apps feel slightly off. We design with
        each platform's idioms in mind, even when sharing a codebase. Tab bars vs. bottom
        navigation. Back-button behaviour. System fonts. Native pickers and sheets. The result
        is two apps that feel right on each platform without doubling the design work.
      </p>

      <h3>Authentication and accounts</h3>
      <p>
        Sign-in with Apple (required for iOS apps that offer third-party login). Sign-in with
        Google. Email and password where appropriate. Magic-link login. Phone number with SMS
        verification. Biometric unlock (Face ID, Touch ID, Android biometric). All wired up to
        a secure backend that handles tokens properly.
      </p>

      <h3>Push notifications, done right</h3>
      <p>
        Push isn't just a technical integration — it's a design discipline. Done badly, users
        disable notifications within a week and never re-enable them. We help you decide what
        actually deserves a notification, build the backend to send them reliably, handle the
        permission prompt at the right moment in the user journey, and give users granular
        controls over what they get. Apple Push Notification service for iOS, Firebase Cloud
        Messaging for Android.
      </p>

      <h3>Payments and subscriptions</h3>
      <p>
        For physical goods or services, Stripe inside the app works fine. For digital goods,
        Apple and Google require their own in-app purchase systems and take 15-30%. We
        integrate StoreKit on iOS and Google Play Billing on Android, including subscription
        management, restoration of purchases on a new device, and grace periods for billing
        issues. We'll explain the rules so you don't get rejected at review.
      </p>

      <h3>Backend and APIs</h3>
      <p>
        Apps need a server. We build it alongside the apps so the API and the client move
        together — no waiting on a separate team, no integration mismatches. Authentication,
        data sync, push delivery, file uploads (with proper handling of large videos),
        background jobs. Hosted on a VPS or managed service depending on scale, with proper
        monitoring.
      </p>

      <h3>App Store and Google Play submission</h3>
      <p>
        This is where projects often stall. Apple's review process can reject you for
        privacy-policy text, for missing in-app purchase handling, for the wrong icon size,
        for using an undocumented API. Google's policy team rejects for permissions you
        request without justification, for content rating mismatches, for ad SDKs they
        consider deceptive. We've been through both review processes many times and prepare
        the submission accordingly. We can submit under your developer accounts (so you keep
        ownership) or help you set up the accounts if you don't have them.
      </p>

      <h3>Privacy, App Tracking Transparency, and the data parts</h3>
      <p>
        iOS App Store Privacy "nutrition labels," ATT prompts for tracking, Google Play data
        safety form, Privacy Manifest files (PrivacyInfo.xcprivacy) — every store wants slightly
        different declarations of what data you collect and why. We fill them out accurately
        and conservatively, and audit your third-party SDKs (analytics, ads, crash reporting)
        for what they actually transmit. If you operate in the UK or EU, GDPR compliance is
        baked in.
      </p>

      <h2>What it costs</h2>
      <p>
        A simple cross-platform app (single feature set, basic backend, both stores) typically
        starts at £15,000 and runs to £35,000 depending on the depth of features. A complex
        app with multiple user roles, real-time features, and platform-specific work is quoted
        per-project, usually £35,000 and up. Apple Developer account is £79/year, Google Play
        Console is a one-time $25, and any third-party services (push providers, analytics,
        backend hosting) are billed to you directly.
      </p>

      <h2>Timeline</h2>
      <p>
        First version (MVP) on both stores typically takes ten to sixteen weeks from kickoff,
        depending on complexity and how quickly we can get through Apple's first review (which
        can take a day or two weeks, unpredictable). Beyond v1, app updates run on whatever
        cadence makes sense — most clients ship monthly or every two months.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
